# Graf view of correlation
def plot_correlation(bank_adj):
    corr = bank_adj.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30, 15))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')
        
plot_correlation(bank_adj)

d - Value counts of all categorical columns.¶

Categorical Variables - finite numbers, defined, listed, boolean ..etc.¶

# Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
# Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
# Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
# CD Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
# Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
# Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Other Variables¶

# ID: Customer ID
# Age: Customer's age in completed years
# Income: Annual income of the customer (000)
# ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
# CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month (000)
# Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (000)
# Family: Family size of the customer
# Experience: #years of professional experience

bank_adj['Personal Loan'] = bank_adj['Personal Loan'].replace({1: 'Yes', 0: 'No', 20.1046: 'N/A'})

# CORRELATION BETWEEN VARIABLES
def plot_correlation(bank_adj):
    corr = bank_adj.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30, 15))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')
        
plot_correlation(bank_adj)

Some variables show correlation (may be not causalization)¶

- Positive correlation (>0.4): age vs experience / Family vs CCAvg / CCAvg vs Incomes¶
- Negative correlation (<-0.4): ZIP code vs Family and CCAVG - need to understand why¶

# CORRELATION BETWEEN VARIABLES
def plot_correlation(Valids):
    corr = Valids.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 20))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')
        
plot_correlation(Valids)

## function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

# FIlter by significant p-value (pval <0.1) and sort descending by Odds ratio
lgcoef = pd.DataFrame(lg.params, columns=['coef'])
lgcoef.loc[:, "Odds_ratio"] = np.exp(lgcoef.coef)
lgcoef['probability'] = lgcoef['Odds_ratio']/(1+lgcoef['Odds_ratio'])
lgcoef['pval']=lg.pvalues
pd.options.display.float_format = '{:.2f}'.format
lgcoef = lgcoef.sort_values(by="Odds_ratio", ascending=False)
print("")
print("Good coefs - Pvalue <= 0.1 ")
print("")
pval_filter = lgcoef['pval']<=0.1
print(lgcoef[pval_filter])
print("")
print("Bad coefs - Pvalue > 0.1 ")
print("")
pval_filter2 = lgcoef['pval']>.1
print(lgcoef[pval_filter2])

6) - Give Business understanding of your model?

It is created 2 models for different segments of use:

first model is more accurated, with high precision, byt for lower number of customers.

second model is more populous, with lower precision, but for more customers on possibility to achieve a personal loan.

its recomended to use the second model on marketing actions, as we can try to get more loans vollume. its recomended to use the fisrt model if its need to more accuracy, as a credit and fraud model/filter.

The results of the model, on a businness view is:

Positive (1) = there is a positive trend of customer get a personal loan Negative (0) = there is a negative trend of customer get a personal loan

The variables that define the trend with logistic regression are:

- 'Income', 
- 'Family', 
- 'CCAvg',
- 'Education', 
- 'Securities Account',
- 'CD Account',
- 'Online',
- 'CreditCard'.
